Rating: 0
For the life of me, I can't understand why people pour sugar into tomato sauce? Anyone who has ever eaten a vine ripened tomato knows how sweet they are. I was raised in America, but my family is from Sicily. Even if you buy good canned plum tomatoes, they are canned vine ripened. Southern Italians were imported spices centuries ago and tend to go more spicy than Northern Italy, so I too would add hot red pepper flakes. I am not a pretentious person who is saying pleeeeze don't do this or that, it's just a sharing to you from my heritage, and sugar is never added. Tomatoes are used fresh from the vine or canned fresh from the vine. Mario Batali from FTV adds small diced carrots to his basic sauce. Though he is obviously Italian, I'm not sure what region of Italy he comes from, though that bright orange hair is telling! If you feel you must 'sweeten' your sauce, try his way before you pour in sugar. Bottom line is that if you feel you must add sugar then please do so, just please know that it really isn't necessary. Honestly, I'm still trying to figure out where that fallacy came from? Seems people add sugar because they think that is what they are supposed to do, or because someone told them that is what they are supposed to do. I guess we all get stuck in that revolving door! Just try it without one time so you at least can have a comparison...you just might be surprised! How many people do you know who pours sugar into a glass of fresh squeezed orange juice? Think about it?

